From 44cdae932cae13cca0b43c2122ed0d446cd77b36 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Fri, 29 May 2026 16:33:48 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 129/174] slub: cap oo_objects at MAX_OBJS_PER_PAGE to avoid
 slab->objects overflow
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

oo_make() clamped order_objects() at OO_MASK (16 bits, 65535), but
struct slab stores the count in a 15-bit bitfield (objects:15), so any
clamp above MAX_OBJS_PER_PAGE silently truncates on the bitfield write:

  slab->objects = oo_objects(oo);  /* 32768 → 0, 65535 → 32767, ... */

With PGCL the kernel PAGE_SIZE can be 1 MB (PAGE_MMUSHIFT=6 on
loongarch's default 16 KB hardware page).  At order 0 a kmalloc-32 slab
then holds 1MB / 32 = 32768 objects, which is min(32768, OO_MASK) =
32768 from oo_make, and the slab.objects bitfield wraps to zero.

obj_exts_alloc_size() then sizes the per-slab obj_cgroup array as
sizeof(slabobj_ext) * 0 = 0, but the slab itself hands out objects
with real indices up to 32767; __memcg_slab_free_hook() does

  off = obj_to_index(s, slab, p[i]);
  obj_ext = slab_obj_ext(slab, obj_exts, off);
  objcg = obj_ext->objcg;

which reads sizeof(slabobj_ext)*off bytes past the (zero-sized)
allocation and returns whatever happens to live there as objcg.  The
subsequent obj_cgroup_uncharge_pages(objcg, ...) dereferences that
garbage pointer and panics — observed on loongarch64 PGCL=6 the first
time single_release() kfrees a 32-byte struct seq_operations, e.g.
during mprotect05 in LTP.

Cap at MAX_OBJS_PER_PAGE so the count always fits in the bitfield.
Slabs of objects smaller than PAGE_SIZE/MAX_OBJS_PER_PAGE (32 bytes
at PAGE_SIZE=1MB) will waste a few trailing object slots per slab,
which is preferable to the silent corruption.

Boot-tested on QEMU loongarch64 virt/la464 at PGCL=6 (PAGE_SIZE=1MB):
pgcl-test 19/0, pgcl-stress 12/0, LTP 71p/3f/27s, no crashes.  Without
this fix every LTP test that calls kfree on a 32-byte allocation
(mprotect05, mremap06, munlock01/02, etc.) ADEs in
obj_cgroup_uncharge_pages, eventually killing init.
---
 mm/slub.c | 12 +++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/mm/slub.c b/mm/slub.c
index 86a251dbae68..b911f0f5eb63 100644
--- a/mm/slub.c
+++ b/mm/slub.c
@@ -586,8 +586,18 @@ static inline struct kmem_cache_order_objects oo_make(unsigned int order,
 {
 	unsigned int nr = order_objects(order, size);
 
+	/*
+	 * Cap at MAX_OBJS_PER_PAGE rather than OO_MASK so that the value
+	 * fits in the 15-bit slab.objects bitfield even when PAGE_SIZE is
+	 * large enough (e.g. 1 MB with PGCL) that a small-object slab
+	 * would otherwise exceed it.  Without this cap, the bitfield write
+	 * silently truncates (32768 → 0 for kmalloc-32 at PAGE_SIZE=1MB),
+	 * obj_exts is sized 0, and obj_to_index() reads past the metadata
+	 * array — corrupting the obj_cgroup pointer on first kfree from
+	 * the slab.
+	 */
 	struct kmem_cache_order_objects x = {
-		(order << OO_SHIFT) + min_t(unsigned int, nr, OO_MASK)
+		(order << OO_SHIFT) + min_t(unsigned int, nr, MAX_OBJS_PER_PAGE)
 	};
 
 	return x;
